"Bertrand C., Van Ypersele J.-P.","Potential role of solar variability as an agent for climate change",1999,"Climatic Change","43","2",,"387","411",,,10.1023/A:1005470900774,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0032839156&partnerID=40&md5=0d16fb2632bf67492446a752936a1af0","Inst. d'Astron. Geophysique G., Univ. Catholique de Louvain, Chemin du Cyclotron 2, B-1348 Louvain-la-Neuve, Belgium","Bertrand, C., Inst. d'Astron. Geophysique G., Univ. Catholique de Louvain, Chemin du Cyclotron 2, B-1348 Louvain-la-Neuve, Belgium; Van Ypersele, J.-P., Inst. d'Astron. Geophysique G., Univ. Catholique de Louvain, Chemin du Cyclotron 2, B-1348 Louvain-la-Neuve, Belgium","Numerical experiments have been carried out with a two-dimensional sector averaged global climate model in order to assess the potential impact of solar variability on the Earth's surface temperature from 1700 to 1992. This was done by investigating the model response to the variations in solar radiation caused by the changes in the Earth's orbital elements, as well as by the changes intrinsic to the Sun. In the absence of a full physical theory able to explain the origin of the observed total solar irradiance variations, three different total solar irradiance reconstructions have been used. A total solar irradiance change due to the photospheric effects incorporated in the Willson and Hudson (1988) parameterization, and the newly reconstructed solar total irradiance variations from the solar models of Hoyt and Schatten (1993) and Lean et al. (1995). Our results indicate that while the influence of the orbital forcing on the annual and global mean surface temperature is negligible at the century time scale, the monthly mean response to this forcing can be quite different from one month to another. The modelled global warming due to the three investigated total solar irradiance reconstructions is insufficient to reproduce the observed 20th century warming. Nevertheless, our simulated surface temperature response to the changes in the Sun's radiant energy output suggests that the Gleissberg cycle (≃88 years) solar forcing should not be neglected in explaining the century-scale climate variations. Finally, spectral analysis seems to point out that the 10- to 12-year oscillations found in the recorded Northern Hemisphere temperature variations from 1700 to 1992 could be unrelated to the solar forcing. Such a result could indicate that the eleven-year period which is frequently found in climate data might be related to oscillations in the atmosphere or oceans, internal to the climate system.",,"climate change; climate forcing; orbital forcing; solar cycle; solar radiation",,,,,,"Berger, A., Long-Term Variations of the Earth's Orbital Elements (1977) Celestial Mech., 15, pp. 53-74; Berger, A., Long-Term Variations of Daily Insolation and Quaternary Climatic Changes (1978) J. Atmos. Sci., 35, pp. 2362-2367; Berger, A., Milankovitch Theory and Climate (1988) Rev. Geophys., 26, pp. 624-657; Bertrand, C., Van Ypersele, J.-P., Berger, A., Volcanic and Solar Impacts on Climate since 1700 (1999) Clim. Dyn., 15, pp. 355-367; Bradley, R.S., Jones, P.D., ""Little Ice Age"" Summer Temperature Variations: Their Nature and Relevance to Recent Global Warming Trends (1993) Holocene, 3, pp. 367-376; Crowley, T.J., North, G.R., (1991) Paleoclimatology, p. 339. , Oxford University Press, New York; Crowley, T.J., Kim, K.-Y., Comparison of Proxy Records of Climate Change and Solar Forcing (1996) Geophys. Res. Lett., 23, pp. 359-362; Cubasch, U., Voss, R., Hegerl, G.C., Waszkewitz, J., Crowley, T.J., Simulation of the Influence of Solar Radiation Variations on the Global Climate with an Ocean-Atmosphere General Circulation Model (1997) Clim. Dyn., 13, pp. 757-767; Dickinson, R., Solar Variability in the Lower Atmosphere (1975) Bull. Amer. Meteorol. Soc., 56, pp. 1240-1248; Dunkerton, T.J., Baldwin, M.P., Modes of Interannual Variability in the Stratosphere (1992) Geophys. Res. Lett., 19, pp. 49-52; Eddy, J.A., The Maunder Minimum (1976) Science, 192, pp. 1189-1202; Eddy, J.A., Variability of the Present and Ancient Sun: A Test of Solar Uniformitarianism (1988) Secular Solar and Geomagnetic Variations, pp. 1-23. , Stephenson, F. R. and Wolfendale, A. (eds.), Kluwer Academic Publishers, Dordrecht; Eddy, J.A., Oeschger, H., The Role of Solar Output Variations (1993) Global Changes in the Perspective of the Past, pp. 279-294. , Eddy, J. A. and Oeschger, H. (eds.), John Wiley and Sons Ltd, Chichester; Fouquart, Y., Bonnel, B., Computations of Solar Heating of the Earth's Atmosphere: A New Parameterization (1980) Beitr. Phys. Atmosph., 53, pp. 35-62; Friis-Christensen, E., Lassen, K., Length of the Solar Cycle: An Indicator of Solar Activity Closely Associated with Climate (1991) Science, 254, pp. 698-700; Gallée, H., Van Ypersele, J.-P., Fichefet, Th., Tricot, Ch., Berger, A., Simulation of the Last Glacial Cycle by a Coupled, Sectorially Averaged Climate-Ice Sheet Model 1. The Climate Model (1991) J. Geophys. Res., 96, pp. 13139-13163; Groveman, B.S., Landsberg, H.E., Simulated Northern Hemisphere Temperature Departures 1579-1880 (1979) Geophys. Res. Lett., 6, pp. 767-769; Haigh, J.D., The Role of Stratospheric Ozone in Modulating the Solar Radiative Forcing of Climate (1994) Nature, 370, pp. 544-546; Haigh, J.D., The Impact of Solar Variability on Climate (1996) Science, 272, pp. 981-984; Hickey, J.R., Alton, B.M., Kyle, H.L., Hoyt, D.V., Total Solar Irradiance Measurements by ERB/Nimbus 7: A Review of Nine Years (1988) Space Sci. Rev., 48, pp. 321-342; Hoffert, M.I., Callegari, A.J., Hsieh, C.-T., The Role of Deep Sea Heat Storage in the Secular Response to Climate Forcing (1980) J. Geophys. Res., 85, pp. 6667-6679; Hoffert, M.I., Frei, A., Narayanan, V.K., Application of Solar Max ACRIM Data to Analysis of Solar-Driven Climatic Variability on Earth (1988) Clim. Change, 13, pp. 267-285; Houghton, J.T., Meira Filho, L.G., Bruce, L., Lee, H., Callande